<TEXT>
ap writer sharon herbaugh based in new delhi 
entered afghanistan on jan 27 to cover the red armys departure and 
the postwithdrawal situation here is her report on the most 
innocent victims of war the children 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
inside the dingy walls of indira gandhi 
childrens hospital doctors and nurses wage their own battle to 
save children from the savagery of the war boobytrapped toys 
rockets bombs and bullets 
mriya a 4yearold from charikar 45 miles north of kabul was 
badly injured three weeks ago by artillery fire as soviet and afghan 
troops attacked moslem guerrillas trying to topple the government 
she suffered broken bones but she was lucky ten of the 12 
people living in her house were killed 
six children injured in a guerrilla rocket attack in kabul were 
brought to the 300bed hospital last week doctors were able to save 
three of them 
when the parents of one of survivor were told their 12yearold 
sons right leg would have to be amputated the father sobbed and 
cried oh let him die let him die hes no good anymore 
even before civil war broke out in 1978 afghanistan had the 
worlds highest child mortality rate according to un statisics 
at least 340 of every 1000 children will not reach their fifth 
birthday and doctors and nurses working in a country where medical 
care is far below accepted standards are struggling to keep the 
number from rising 
we want to get away from politics as much as possible here 
said dr abdul salam jalali head of the 102member hospital staff 
there may be sons of mujahedeen guerrilla commanders here we 
dont ask they are children they are not directly involved in the 
war 
some children have been injured by toys rigged with explosives 
and left on streets it is unclear whether the booby traps are the 
work of afghan government forces or the guerrillas 
more than 1 million people have died in the war which has 
severely strained the hospital built in 1972 by india and named 
after its late prime minister it is always crowded and cockroaches 
climb the walls 
sometimes we put two or three patients in one bed sometimes we 
put them in a corridor or on the floor but we never refuse a 
patient and its all completely free jalali said 
the cost of medicine and food has soared and consumed the 
hospitals budget 
all medicine is imported and getting it to the hospital is 
difficult because of fuel shortages and guerrilla attacks on 
government convoys a lack of supplies often forces doctors to reuse 
bandages 
the war also has made it harder for afghanistans poor to afford 
nutritional food and has diverted attention from child health care 
they dont bother about these problems jalali said they 
just want to stay alive and when they finally do bring them to the 
hospital its often too late 
malnutrition is our main problem this has been going on for 
years but now its worse he said 
emaciated children their resistance weakened by lack of food 
suffer tuberculosis meningitis and other diseases 
in the final weeks of the soviet troop withdrawal kabul suffered 
severe food shortages vegetable and fruit stands at city markets 
now are full but prices are far beyond the reach of the poor 
the situation is worse for children in other parts of afghanistan 
khagal mohammad who livesin the laghman province east of kabul 
weighs about 15 pounds the normal weight for a 7monthold baby he 
is 4 years old 
mayabim a 5yearold from central hazarajat weighs only 20 
pounds and suffers from tuberculosis meningitis and brain damage 
we were too far away it took us too long to get here said 
his sobbing mother gulandam 
unicef the red crescent a moslem organization similar to the 
red cross and other charities also care for children but say more 
help is needed 
peace is a prerequisite and peace for afghanistan is not yet 
on the horizon said unicef spokesman vincent oreilley 
</TEXT>
