the national weather service is facing a 
shortage of money and a reorganization that could lead to the 
closing of many local weather offices over the next several years 
the money available for the current fiscal year likely wont 
cover costs and the budget under discussion for next year could be 
even worse 
at the same time administrators are trying to complete a 
longrange reorganization plan aimed at consolidating offices 
through the use of new electronic equipment 
the weather service currently has nearly 250 local offices across 
the country and administrators hope to keep most of them running for 
at least the next few years while automated observation equipment 
can be purchased and installed 
then closings could be phased in gradually perhaps taking as 
long as a decade according to agency officials 
but the budget crunch is more immediate 
the current fiscal year is expected to end with the weather 
service short between 10 million and 28 million the shortfall has 
prompted a hiring freeze and a search for other savings according 
to several national oceanic and atmospheric administration officials 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
noaa spending proposed by former president reagan for fiscal 
1990 meanwhile was set at 114 billion down from 119 billion 
in the current fiscal year 
while the national weather services portion of the noaa budget 
increases slightly under the budget that includes money to buy new 
radar and observation equipment and a supercomputer 
according to congressional sources the reagan proposal called 
for closing as many as 62 local weather offices this year and 77 
more next year as part of a consolidation move that would shift many 
specialized forecasting tasks to private weather services 
